# Commit messages (Conventional Commits)

Follow [Conventional Commits 1.0.0](https://www.conventionalcommits.org/en/v1.0.0/#summary).

## Format

```text
<type>[optional scope][optional !]: <description>

[optional body]

[optional footer(s)]
```

- **One blank line** between subject and body.
- **Subject:** imperative mood (“add”, not “added”), **lowercase type**, no trailing period. Prefer **≤~72 chars** for readable one-line logs; repo hook rejects above **120**. Say **what changed** (behavior, API, invariant)—not “work was done on X.”
- **Scope:** optional noun in parentheses; use a real area of this repo when it helps: `frontend`, `ingestion`, `analysis`, `trends`, `core`, `repo` (tooling/layout), `docs`, `colearn` (only if the commit is mostly curriculum/docs there).
- **Breaking changes:** `feat(api)!: …` and/or footer `BREAKING CHANGE: …` (uppercase token).

## Types (pick one primary)

| Type | Use for |
|------|--------|
| `feat` | New behavior / API / UI capability |
| `fix` | Bug fix |
| `perf` | Performance-only change |
| `refactor` | Behavior-preserving code move/reshape |
| `test` | Tests only |
| `build` | Build system, deps, packaging |
| `ci` | CI config |
| `chore` | Maintenance, ignores, non-code churn |
| `docs` | README, comments meant as docs |
| `revert` | Reverts a prior commit (reference SHA in footer if useful) |

Other types from the ecosystem (`style`, etc.) are fine if they fit; **do not** invent vague types.

## Vocabulary (meaningful, not marketing)

**Avoid filler / LLM-slop verbs** in subject and body: _enhance_, _introduce_, _leverage_, _streamline_, _facilitate_, _empower_, _utilize_, _holistic_, _seamless_, _robust_, _comprehensive_, _various_, _delve_, _optimize_ (unless the commit is a measured perf change—then use `perf` and name the metric).

**Prefer concrete verbs** that a reviewer can map to a diff: `add`, `remove`, `fix`, `split`, `merge`, `rename`, `move`, `wire`, `guard`, `validate`, `tighten`, `relax`, `narrow`, `widen`, `cache`, `persist`, `scope`, `tenant-scope`, `debounce`, `truncate`, `ignore`, `bump`, `drop`, `raise` (e.g. limit), `lower`.

**Bad → better (subject):**

- `feat(x): enhance validation` → `feat(x): reject invalid human_value for theme corrections`
- `fix(x): improve error handling` → `fix(x): return 422 when theme slug unknown`
- `chore(x): introduce helper` → `chore(x): extract theme slug normalizer`

## Body (when needed)

- Prefer **3–6 short bullets**, each an **outcome** (what changed for the user or system), not a file-by-file narration.
- Avoid repeating the subject; avoid duplicate bullets that say the same thing with different components.
- No markdown heading inside the commit body unless the user asked for it.

## Examples (good)

```text
feat(frontend): click themes in explorer to apply list filter

- thread filter callback from ExplorerPage through detail panel and rows
```

```text
chore(repo): ignore Celery Beat schedule database

- add celerybeat-schedule* to gitignore
```

```text
fix(analysis): cap batch size when Redis payload exceeds limit
```

## Examples (bad)

- Subject too long or title-case Every Word.
- Slop verbs (`enhance`, `introduce`, `leverage`, …) with no observable behavior.
- Body that only lists filenames without intent (`- Update foo.tsx`).
- Multiple unrelated concerns in one commit message (split commits instead).
